git init 
git config --global user.name
git config --global user.email
git add "filename"
git add .  - Bring your file to the staging area (for building commit)
git rm "file/path"
git log (history of commits)
git log --oneline (quick history of commits)
git diff (content difference)
git show ['SHA'] - tells all the details of commits
git blame - shows line wise all the changes
git status -  tells what modification happend in the files
git reset --hard [SHA] - change Head to mentioned commit SHA-hash (Problem - if you want to revert a commit in middle of the commit chain(linked-list type) -  You can't')
git revert [SHA] - will help you revert any specific commit anywhere from the linked-list chain of commits.
git remote --v  - tells about do you have any Remote linked to push your code or not.
git remote add origin [Repo_link] - adds your repo remote to the working directory.
git push -u origin main - help you to push upstream (-u) to origin in main branch.
git branch - tells in which branch you are in.
git branch <branch name> - Create a branch


GitHub is a cloud service that hosts Git repositories remotely and provides tools for collaboration (like pull requests, issues, code reviews). Git maintains commit history; GitHub just stores and shares it.




Visual representation : -

┌────────────────────────┐        ┌─────────────────────┐        ┌───────────────────────┐
│    WORKING DIRECTORY   │        │    STAGING AREA     │        │     GIT REPOSITORY     │
│ (Your actual files on  │  git add   (Index file)      │ git commit   (.git/objects)   │
│   your machine)        │  ───────→│  Snapshot builder  │──────────→│ (History of commits) │
└────────────────────────┘        └─────────────────────┘        └───────────────────────┘
         │                          │                                  │
         │ edit, delete, create     │ blobs + trees stored             │ commit = metadata + snapshot
         ▼                          ▼                                  ▼
   “Untracked / Modified”     “Staged changes”                   “Permanent version”



GIT BRANCHING :- Useful when we are working in a company and there are so many developers
 - Pushing commits of all developers in a one branch will polute the commits and it makes it hard to revert any perticular commit ( A , A , A , A , A , B , B , A , B , A ) -if you have to revert B's' commits than it will be hard to revert. Thats why there is the concept of branching.

 visual representation : -

 -- PARALLEL BRANCHES VIEW
master:          A1 —— A2 —— A3 —— A4 —— A5
feature/login:                 \—— F1 —— F2 —— F3
bugfix/session-timeout:                    \—— B1 —— B2

master (after merging feature/login):
    A1 —— A2 —— A3 —— F1 —— F2 —— F3 —— A4 —— A5